INSERT INTO `features` VALUES (42,31,'Use of Employement Header - jf','The following are fields which are delivered by default by Core HR:\r\n	Shown By default\r\n•	Display Name\r\n•	Person Number\r\n•	Assignment Number\r\n•	Job\r\n•	Position\r\n•	Department\r\n•	Location\r\n•	Manager\r\n\r\nHidden Fields\r\n1.	WorkPhoneNumber\r\n2.	Home Phone Number\r\n3.	MobilePhoneNumber\r\n4.	HomeAddress\r\n5.	NationalIdentifier\r\n6.	LegalEmployer\r\n7.	Country\r\n8.	WorkRelationshipStatus\r\n9.	WorkEmailAddress\r\n10.	PersonalEmailAddress\r\n11.	BirthDate\r\n12.	MailingAddress\r\n13.	EnterpriseStartDate\r\n14.	StartDate\r\n15.	LegalEmployerSeniorityDate\r\n16.	WorkingAtHome\r\n17.	WorkingHours\r\n18.	StartTime\r\n19.	EndTime\r\n20.	AssignmentCategory\r\n\r\nWorker’s Picture - Although the header is delivered with the default to have the section open for a worker’s picture to be imported, Time and Labor can hide the picture on the page.  If a picture is to be displayed, it is maintained in two places:  1.  Manage Personal Information - the HR Specialist can upload the picture. 2.  My Portrait - the Worker can upload the picture themselves.  \r\n','2011-04-13 00:20:53','2011-05-03 21:24:22',1,'Must Have','',NULL),(1218,125,'No Name','test','2011-04-13 22:38:21','2011-04-14 21:59:15',1,'Must Have','2.0',NULL),(1219,126,'Manage Time Category Page','<p> Time Category search will allow for the access to time \n                    categories as well as create, duplicate, view, edit or delete existing time categories<p>\n                    <p>Must have features to support existing functionality:</p>\n\n     <p> Basic/Advanced Search Page for Time Categories</p>\n<p>Basic Search fields:</p>\n\n<li>   Time Category Name</li>\n\n<li>    Time Category Description </li>\n\n<p>Advanced Search Fields</p>\n\n<li> Time Category Name</li>\n\n<li> Time Category Description</li>\n\n<li> Time Attribute field:  any time attribute field which is specified in an existing time category</li>\n\n<li> Usage</li>\n\n<li> Time Attribute value</li>\n\n<li> Operator: this field is coupled with all of the advanced search fields, to allow more flexibility to search</li>\n\n<p>The options for the operator values are:</p>\n    <li>Starts With: </li> searches for records where the first characters\n       match the given text string.\n     <li>Ends With: </li> searches for records where the last characters the\n       given text string.\n     <li>Equals: </li> searches for records that match the text string exactly\n       (ignoring case).\n       Replaces the “Is” operator in BLAF 3.x.\n     <li>Does Not Equal: </li> searches for records that do not match the text\n       string exactly (ignoring case).\n       Replaces the “Is Not” operator in BLAF 3.x.\n     <li>Contains: </li> searches for records that contain the given text string.\n       Oracle Text and OSES Contains operator\n       SQL LIKE operator\n     <li>Does Not Contain: </li> searches for records that do not contain the\n       given text string.\n       Not supported for SQL search.\n       Not recommended for Oracle Text and OSES driven search for\n       performance reasons.\n       Use only if there is a strong use case approved by Apps UX and\n       Performance.\n     <li>Is Blank: </li> searches for records that do not have a value (i.e.\n       are null).\n       When Is Blank is chosen, the value field is hidden.\n     <li>Is Not Blank: </li> searches for records that have any value (i.e.\n       are not null).\n       When Is Not Blank is chosen, the value field is hidden.\n<br/><br/>\n <p>Default Conditions for Text Fields:</p>\n\n     <li>Starts With: If search technology is SQL and widget is a Text\n       Box or LOV. </li>\n     <li>Contains: If Search Technology is Oracle Text or OSES and\n       widget is a Text Box or LOV.</li>\n     <li>Equals: If widget is a Choice List.</li>\n\n    Also allow for wildcard search in each field.\n\n<p>Search Results Section:</p>\n\n<li>    Time Category Name- user defined name for time category</li>\n\n<li>    Usage: a hyperlinked list of Time Entry Rules, Time Calculation Rules or Time Audit Rules that contain this Time Category.  When clicking this hyperlink, a pop up page will provide details on the rules impacted.</li>\n\n<li>    Description: user defined description of the time category</li>\n\n<li>    The search results should initially default to the last 10 time categories created.  There will be seeded time categories which will also be listed</li>\n\n<li>    Actions Menu</li>\n<p>\n<li>  Create: create a new time category</li>\n<li>  Delete: delete an existing time category, only if it is not currently used in another object such as rule or balance</li>\n\n<li>  Duplicate: select an existing time category and duplicate it, changing the name and description.  All other values will copy over from the selected time category</li>\n\n<li>  Edit: select an existing time category for update. </li>\n</p>\n\n<li>    Toolbar Menu: following are the icons in the toolbar which represent the menu actions</li>\n<p>\n<li>  Add</li>\n\n<li>  Delete</li>\n\n<li>  Duplicate</li>\n\n<li>  Edit   </li></p>   ','2011-04-13 22:38:21','2011-04-13 22:38:21',NULL,'Must Have','2.0',NULL),(1220,126,'Create Time Category Page','<p> Time Categories can be simple listing of possible values entered in the timecard, or it can be a more complex combination of values that are used in a comparison.  These categories are used to trigger validations and rules on time entries, for summary timecard analytics, or for balances used in rules.   A time category itself can be a nested time category of other time categories.   In Fusion, the attributes available for compiling a time category will be time attribute fields or other time categories. <p>\n                   <p>The time category definition requires the flexibility for a user to add as many conditions as they need to summarize time attributes.  It is also required to group these conditions into logical expressions, with comparisons between these expressions.  In order to offer this flexibility, we will use the Fusion Structured Condition Builder Guideline.  Reference to this Guideline: http://fusiongps.us.oracle.com/guidelines/content/guidelines/expressionbuilder/conditions/index.htm#StructuredCondition. Using this structured condition builder design approach will make it easier for users to uptake the feature, as they will have exposure to this design in other applications, such as AMX approval rules setup.<p>\n                   <p>Create Time Category page</p>\n\n<p>Create Time Category : Page Name</p>\n\n<p>Tags: enable the web center icon to allow user to define tags on time categories</p>\n\n         <p>Summary Information:</p>\n<p>\n   <li> Name: Time Category Name</li>\n\n <li>   Description: Time Category Description</li>\n</p>\n    <p>     Time Category Condition Pane</p>\n\n    <p> Actions Menu</p>\n    <p>\n          <li> Add</li>\n          <li> Duplicate</li>\n            \n          <li>Delete</li>\n            \n          <li>Add Nest</li>\n          <li> Delete Nest </li>\n</p>\n<p>Actions Behavior</p>\n<p>\n<li>  Add New Row (No Selection): A new row is inserted after the last row in the table.</li>\n\n<li>    Add New Row (Row Selected): A new row is added below the selected row.</li>\n\n<li> Add New Row (Multiple Rows Selected): One new row is added below the last selected row.</li>\n\n<li>    Duplicate Row: The duplicate row is added below the selected row.</li>\n\n<li> Duplicate Multiple Rows: The group of duplicated rows is added below the selected group.</li>\n\n<li>    Duplicate Noncontiguous Duplication: The group of duplicated rows is added below the selected row or group of rows.\nExample: If the user selects rows 2, 3, and 5, and then clicks the Duplicate icon, the duplicated rows appear below the 2 and 3 grouping and below row 5. \n</li>\n<li>    Delete Row: Deletes the selected row from the table. All rows below it move up to fill the space.</li>\n\n<li>    Add Nest: to add a nested condtion with its own set of parentheses within an existing condition</li>\n\n<li>    Delete Nest: to select a nested condition and delete</li>\n</p>\n    <p> Toolbar Icons</p>\n    <p>\n          <li> Add (  )   Add new row</li>\n          <li> Duplicate (  )   Duplicate selected row or rows</li>\n          <li> Delete (  )  Delete selected row or rows</li>\n           \n          <li> Add Parentheses (  ): Nests and indents selected rows.</li>\n          <li> Delete Parentheses (  ): Deletes the nesting and indention of selected rows.</li>\n          <li> Up and Down Arrows – to allow the user to select a row and move it above or below another condition.</li>\n          <li> Import Time Category button – to allow the user to select a row and import a time category below that condition.  This allows the ability to bring into the current definition of a new time category, a pre-existing time category, i.e.  nest one time category within another.  Once an existing time category is imported into the current time category definition, it will be displayed in read-only format, along with its attribute fields and values.  This will protect the original definition of the nested time category. Insert Time Category action should be available at any level and part of collapsible section.\n</li>\n</p>\n<p>Fields displayed in the Condition Pane</p>\n<p>\n    <li> Row Selector: A check box and row highlighting is used to indicate selection for a given condition</li>\n    <li> Parentheses:  Added before and after each condition grouping, different levels of parantheses based on nested conditions</li>\n    <li> Time Attribute field: A smart choice list which contains a set of attributes defined within the Time and Labor data dictionary.  Examples of Time Attributes include Project ID, Hours Type, Task, Expenditure Type, Department, Customer.   Users cannot add new attributes to the choice list.  </li>\n    <li> Condition:  A choice list of the following options for the conditions of the time attribute values to exist to trigger the time category:</li>\n\n<ol><li>    Any Value</li>\n\n<li>    Empty Field (Null Value)</li>\n\n<li>    Value Set</li>\n\n<li>    Specific Value</li>\n<ol>\n\n<li>      Time Attribute Value: A choice list of the values related to the selected time attribute field.</li>\n\n<li>         Logical Operator: This combines two conditions to return a set of filtered results.</li>\n\n        <ol><li> Values: AND or  OR</li>\n          <li> Set to AND by default.</li>\n          <li> This field should be hidden in the last row of the table </li>\n</ol>\n \n\n<p>Page Actions:</p>\n\n    <li> Validate:  The combination of conditions are checked to ensure the logic is grouped correctly</li>\n          <ol><li> If errors are found, a message is displayed.</li>\n          <li> User can validate the condition at any time.</li>\n          <li> Validation is performed when the user clicks the Validate button or exits the page. Conditions should be verified to: </li>\n</ol>\n<li>  Check that data has been entered into required fields.</li>\n\n<li>  Check that a selection has been made in each of the Attribute, Operator, Value and Logical Operator fields.</li>\n\n<li>   Check that no invalid characters have been entered in the Value field. Invalid characters include: @, >, %, and so on.</li>\n\n    <li> Save: Saves the changes, updates the object information in the base table.</li>\n          <ol><li> Condition is checked for errors. If errors are present a message is displayed.</li>\n          <li> The time category should not be saved with errors because then inaccurate time categories may be used</li><ol>\n    <li> Save and Close: Saves the changes and closes the window.</li>\n          <li> Condition is checked for errors. If errors are present a message is displayed.  </li></ol>\n    <li> Cancel: Cancels the transaction, closes the page and returns user to the referencing page.</li>\n\n \n<p>\n<li>Additional Features of the Condition Pane</li>\n\n         <ol><li>Show/Hide Collapsible Sections: Each logic grouping identified with its set of  parentheses can be collapsed in a section, with a summary Comments field displayed, to make it easier to read the content of a time category which has multiple logic groupings.  Each logic grouping should be collapsible to allow for a distinct summary of what each logic defines. The summary is provided by the Comments field.</li>\n\n         <li>Comments Field: should be 30 characters in length and part of collapsible section for logic grouping.  When the section is collapsed, this field is still open for display to the user.</li>\n\n \n\n        <li>View Resolved Time Category: (nice to have) this  last section will dynamically provide an“English” sentence which retrieves the selected Time Entry Attribute values and places them within the logic statement selected, with the use of “and” and “or” operator in between the value listing.  This sentence will get updated as the time entry attributes are associated to the appropriate logic columns.\n</li></ol>\n </p>\n\n<p>Accessibility Requirements</p>\n<p>\nAlthough there are no visible column labels in the Condition pane, the following needs to be coded for accessibility requirements:\n\n<li>    Field labels (for example, attribute, operator, and so on) are hidden but must be labeled.</li>\n\n<li>    Each row in the condition must be identified uniquely.\nExample:  Attribute: Row 1, Operator: Row 1</li>\n</p>\n \n<p>\n<li>Time Category examples</li>\n\n<ol><li> Unscheduled Hours</li>\n\nDay = Saturday or Day=Sunday\n\nAnd\n\nHours Type = Regular or Jury or Holiday or Overtime or Doubletime\n\n \n\n<li>  Special Pay</li>\n\n(Day=Saturday or Sunday\n\nAnd\n\nHours Type= Compensation Earned, Call In Pay, Double Overtime)\n\nOR\n\nHours Type= Compensation Earned, Call In Pay, Double Overtime\n\n \n\n<li>  Project Development Cost</li>\n\nProject ID is Design or Development or Testing\n\nAnd\n\nTask=Any Value\n\nAnd Expenditure Types is Straight Time or Overtime\n\nAnd\n\nCost Code is 123, or 456, or 789\n</p>\n \n\n \n\n<li>Edit Time Category: all fields and behavior will be available for update in the Edit Time Category display.  </li>\n    ','2011-04-13 22:38:21','2011-04-13 22:38:21',NULL,'Must Have','2.0',NULL),(1221,127,'General Worklist: Timecard Summary Approval Display','A user needs the ability to view a listing of all timecards that require approval in one view.  This summary view should allow for a single timecard to be approved or multiple timecards to be approved (rejected) at one time. The user actions on the timecards would include approving, rejecting, reassigning or requesting more information.\n\nThe approver needs to be able to enter comments for each timecard being approved or rejected, so the approval comments will route to the originator of the timecard.\n\nOne display of the timecards requiring approval will be in the federated version of the Worlist table which will appear in the Welcome tab of the Fusion Home page This component displays all open workflow tasks (approvals and other requests for action) and notifications (FYI tasks) for the current user.\n\nWorklist tasks are displayed using the table as shown below. Selecting an item in the table launches the corresponding task details page in its own browser window without the Fusion chrome. Both single-select and multi-select actions are supported by this table.\n\nTable columns displayed:\n\n·     Title\n\n·     Status\n\n·     From\n\n·     Assigned Date\n\n \n\nActions menu:\n\no     Custom action\n\no     Claim\n\no     Resume\n\no     Renew\n\no     Submit\n\no     Dismiss\n\no     -----\n\no     Request Information...\n\no     Delegate...\n\no     Reassign...\n\no     Push Back...\n\no     Escalate...\n\no     -----\n\no     Release\n\no     Suspend\n\no     -----\n\no     Create To Do Task... ','2011-04-13 22:38:21','2011-04-13 22:38:21',NULL,'Must Have','2.0',NULL),(1222,127,'General Worklist: Timecard Detail Approval Display','Ability to drill down into the detail of a timecard, to see all time requiring approval, and be able to approve from the detail view.  The user actions on the timecard would include approving, rejecting, reassigning or requesting more information.\n\nThe Timecard Details section should be a display similar to what is viewed on the Timecard Review page, which would include in a read only display, the time entry details, processed results, and other sections as configured in the Time Entry Page Composer.\n\nAdditionally, there should be a link to the actual timecard from the detail display page, in case the approver needs to navigate to the actual timecard for more information.','2011-04-13 22:38:21','2011-04-13 22:38:21',NULL,'Must Have','2.0',NULL),(1223,127,'Custom Worklist: Timecard Summary Approval Display','To provide the timecard approver with a filtered list of just timecards requiring approval, along with other data which assist in making informed approver decisions, there will be a custom worklist view of Timecards Requiring Approval.  This worklist display will be available in the landing page of the Timecards Workarea for managers or timekeepers who are granted the duty role of timecard approval. \n\nThis summary view should allow for a single timecard to be approved or multiple timecards to be approved at one time. The user actions on the timecards would include approving, rejecting, reassigning or requesting more information.\n\nAdditionally, there should be information specific for the timecard approver to make a better decision to approve or reject the timecard.  The custom worklist should include the following columns:\n\n \n\no     Person Name\n\no     Role\n\no     Timecard Period\n\no     Timecard Status\n\no     Total Hours\n\no     Premium Hours\n\no     Non Worked Hours\n\no     Submission Date\n\nThe table should include Search and Advanced Search options in the toolbar to assist in finding certain timecards requiring approval.  These search items were also available in Mass Timecard Approval feature in EBS OTL R12\n\n§     Basic Search:   Person, Timecard Period,  Status\n\n§     Advanced Search: \n- Timecard Fields: Detail Comment,  Timecard comment, Timecard Period, Timecard Status, Timecard Submission Date, Totals Hours  , also any other timecard fields which have been defined in the time entry page composer by the user , should be available from Add Field choice list \n- Comparative Operator: Equals To, Greater Than, Greater Than or Equals To, Less Than, Less Than or Equals To, Like, Not Equal To, Not Like \n- Value: Open Field  \n- Logical Operator:   And, Or','2011-04-13 22:38:21','2011-04-13 22:38:21',NULL,'Must Have','2.0',NULL),(1224,127,'Custom Worklist: Configurable Columns in Timecard Summary Approval','In addition to the columns added for the custom view of timecard approvals,  we should also provide extra columns that could be added by the user when defining a view.  These additional columns allows a user to add summary fields that are specific to their business, to aide in the process of approving timecards.  There should be an “Add Field” component, which allows the user to select from summarization fields which are defined in Time Entry Editor for the Time Summary table displayed in the Timecard.  These additional fields will be dependent on what the customer selects as their timecard summarizations to track in the Time Summary section of the Layout Set.  They could be such things as Project and Task, or Billable/Non-Billable or Worked/Non-Worked Hours.','2011-04-13 22:38:21','2011-04-13 22:38:21',NULL,'Must Have','2.0',NULL),(1225,127,'Custom Worklist:  Timecard Detail Approval Page','a.     Would need the ability to drill down into the detail of a timecard, to see all time requiring approval, and be able to approve from the detail view.  The user actions on the timecard would include approve, reject, delegate, transfer or request more information.\n\nb.     Would need the ability to view the timecard detail, as displayed in the Timecard Review page, without any pop-ups or drill in pages.  There will be a configuration for the setup of the timecard detail approval notification page in the Time Entry Page Composer.\n\nc.     Would need to view a tablular and graphical approval history of which approvers have taken action and which approvers have yet to take action\n\nd.     Would need a hyperlink to the viewable timecard page, in case the approver needed more detail within the timecard. Once viewed, the user needs to be able to navigate back to the approval notification.\n\ne.     Would need a section for Comments, for the approver to make comments if the timecard has been approved or rejected.\n\nf.     Would be nice to have a section for Audit Log, to see the users who have interacted with the timecard and what action they took.  (Fields to include:  user name, action taken, date and timestamp, role)','2011-04-13 22:38:21','2011-04-13 22:38:21',NULL,'Must Have','2.0',NULL),(1226,127,'Worklist: Timecard Detail Approval Page – Display Change and Late Audit Entries','For users, with time audit rules associated to them, they will have additional entries to make on a Time Audit page, in which they need to enter reasons and comments for changes to time entries.  The Timecard Detail Approval Display should include the Change and Late Audit sections in the Timecard Details section .   Ideally, the change and late audit sections we display on the  Time Audit Review page will be used on the Timecard Detail Approval page. Alternatively, if there is not enough space to display these sections, the user should be taken to the full viewable timecard page by hyperlink to see all relevant sections.','2011-04-13 22:38:21','2011-04-13 22:38:21',NULL,'Must Have','2.0',NULL),(1227,127,'Worklist: Approval Actions ','Support the following  AMX Approval Actions for both the Approval Notification Detail page as well as the Custom Timecard Approval Summary Workllist page.\n\no     Approve – Approve the timecard, providing any comments in the approval notification if needed.  Should be a page level action button on the approval notification page and Custom Timecard Approval Summary Worklist page.\n\no     Reject – Reject the timecard and place comments in the approval notification explaining what has been rejected.  Should be a page level action button on the approval notification page and Custom Timecard Approval Summary Worklist page.\n\no     Request More Information – email notification sent to worker, email and no action needed on the  timecard,.  This allows the approver  to ask a question to the requester or anyone in the approval list before making a decision..  This option should be part of an Actions menu dropdown in the approval notification page.  It can be a toolbar button on the Custom Timecard Approval Summary Worklist page.\n\no     Reassign... – there are two options from this action in its dialog:\n\n§     Delegate - Forwards task to another user, without change in ownership.\n\n§     Transfer - Forwards and changes ownership to another user.\n\nThe option of Reassign with the two sub-options of Delegate and Transfer should be part of an Actions menu dropdown in the approval notification page.  It can be a toolbar button on the Custom Timecard Approval Summary Worklist page.','2011-04-13 22:38:21','2011-04-13 22:38:21',NULL,'Must Have','2.0',NULL),(1228,127,'Worklist: Require User to Open Timecard before Approval','A business requirement may be that an approver must open a timecard to review it before approving it.  In order to enforce this condition, there would need to be the prevention of approving or rejecting a timecard from the summary approval worklist page in either the General Worklist or Custom Worklist view.   The user would need to do to the Detail Approval page to take the approval action necessary.  Currently there is a Enhancement Request registered with AMX to provide for this requirement:\n\n \n\nAMX Enhancement Request:  REQUIRE TO OPEN THE TIMECARD BEFORE BEING ABLE TO ACT ON IT – configuration needed in AMX, parameter set so when user clicks on Approve or Reject action, cannot take action unless open notification.','2011-04-13 22:38:21','2011-04-13 22:38:21',NULL,'Must Have','2.0',NULL),(1229,127,'Worklist: Approval Comments','An approver should be able to enter comments against a timecard with the approval or rejection of a timecard.  If the approver is making multiple approvals or rejections from the summary worklist page, there should be a pop-up to allow the approver to make comments against each timecard prior to taking the action. \n\n \n\nOne option would be to have the comment field in the worklist table, the second option would be to have a dialog box that allows comments to be entered for the different timecards selected.\n\n \n\nCurrently there is an enhancement request open with AMX to allow for the entry of comments against multiple timecards for a multiple approval or rejection of timecards:\n\nBEING ABLE TO ENTER COMMENTS AGAINST A TIMECARD PRIOR APPROVE/REJECT: (MUST HAVE) \nMass Comment Entry before applying the action (approve, reject, whatever)','2011-04-13 22:38:21','2011-04-13 22:38:21',NULL,'Must Have','2.0',NULL),(1230,127,'Display Approval Results on Timecard','The results of the approval or rejection of a timecard needs to be consolidated for display in the timecard.  There may be multiple approvers who may have approved or rejected different blocks of time within the timecard.  Since the timecard is one entity viewed by the user, it needs to easily display which time entries have been approved or rejected, by which approver and any comments related to the actions. \n\na.   The user will see the Timecard Status on the Timecard:\n\nRejected: If there is at least one time entry which is rejected, the whole timecard status will be rejected\n\nApproved:  If all time entries for that timecard is approved, the whole timecard is approved\n\nSubmitted:  The timecard will remain in this state pending approver or if the user needs to respond to an email request for information from one of the timecard approvers.\n\n \n\nb.   There will be an Approver Comments pop-up dialog box which will display the following information to the timecard user:\n\nApprover Name  Role  Approver Comments\n\nIf any approver has rejected part or all of the timecard, his comments should specify what was rejected and what needs to be resolved.  The Approval Comments will pop-up in a dialog when the user enters the timecard if there are any comments to display.  If the user closes the pop-up dialog box by clicking on “OK” button, then he needs to be able to access a “View Approver Comments” toolbar button to view the comments again.  The approval comments are associated with the current version of the timecard being reviewed.  If the timecard is modified and resubmitted, new approval comments will be associated to the “newer” version of the timecard.','2011-04-13 22:38:21','2011-04-13 22:38:21',NULL,'Must Have','2.0',NULL),(1231,127,'Override Approver  (AMX)','The timecard will no longer display an “override approver” field for the user to enter a name. The main reason for the override approver field displayed on the timecard was if the approver was on vacation. The other example is that a worker has a change in Projects reported, and thus a change in Project Manager who would approve his timecard.  In this example, the timecard approval rule can be setup to be based on Project ID, to derive the correct Project Manager for approval routing.\n\n \n\nInstead, the AMX action of “Delegate” can be used by the approver who will not be available, to delegate the approval to another. \n\n \n\nA second approach recommended by AMX was to have the customer define an “owner” for the timecard approval transactions, so they could intercede if the approval transaction was “stuck” in the approval chain\n\n \n\nIt is still be determined if the above approach is workable for the temporary change of approvers needed.  The attributes of the “Override Approver” field on the timecard was the following:\n\n \n\nü     Provide the ability for a user to enter a name for an override approver in the routing of the timecard.\n\nü     The override approver will take the place of any other approvers originally designated in the approval routing for that timecard. \n\nü     This override approver will only be defined for that particular timecard.\n\nü     Provide the ability to define a default override approver, to allow the user to easily find the name of an override approver that he has selected on prior occasions.','2011-04-13 22:38:21','2011-04-13 22:38:21',NULL,'Must Have','2.0',NULL),(1232,127,'Approval Routing: Allow for Parallel or Serial Approvers for a Timecard (AMX)','Provide the ability to route a timecard for approval in multiple methods:\n\nü     Serial (sequential) routing which will allow a timecard to be routed to one approver, upon approval from the prior approver\n\nü     Parallel routing which allows the timecard to be routed to multiple approvers simultaneously:\n\no     Sections of the Timecard can be routed in parallel to one or more approvers within one application like Payroll.  This covers Entry Level Approvals functionality which existed in EBS OTL R12.  We will be able to send a row of timecard data to each approver for which it is relevant for them.  The sections of the timecard matrix which are relevant will display in the Timecard Details section.\n\no     The whole Timecard can be routed in parallel to one or more approvers in different applications like HR, Payroll and Projects\n\n \n\n(Note:  We will not continue the requirement for a sequential application dependency that all approvers from one application will not receive the timecard for approval until the timecard has been acted upon by another application.)','2011-04-13 22:38:22','2011-04-13 22:38:22',NULL,'Must Have','2.0',NULL),(1233,127,'Approval Routing: Package Time for Approvers (AMX)','The following are the requirements for packaging portions of a timecard to be routed to different approvers:\n\n \n\nü     Allow for the user to define certain fields of the timecard to be routed to different approvers based on defined approval rules\n\nü     The segmentation or fragmentation of the timecard allow for the approver to only see fields that are critical to them for approval, and also secures other fields that they should not see from the approval display\n\nü     The segmentation of the timecard fields can be done by application via the use of time categories.  These time categories can summarize time entries by time attributes. \n\n \n\nü     (Moved to Out of Scope region )Timecards can be sent for approval with a priority order to various applications','2011-04-13 22:38:22','2011-04-13 22:38:22',NULL,'Must Have','2.0',NULL),(1234,127,'Approval Routing: Flexibility of Defining the Approvers (AMX)','hese are the current default approval mechanisms which the Time and Labor Approval Styles offers, which should be offered in Approval Groups in AMX:\n\nü     HR Supervisor – ability to specify the worker’s HR Supervisor\n\nü     Specific Person – ability to define a specific person\n\nü     Project Manager – ability to define the worker’s project manager based on the project that the employee reported time against\n\nü     Auto Approve – Allowance for auto approval of the timecard\n\nü     Entry Level Approver – different approvers within an application(s) who see portions of the timecard requiring approval.\n\n \n\nThis flexibility of defining such criteria should be covered by Dynamic Approval Groups setup in AMX.\n\n \n\nNote:  Fast formula will no longer be supported for defining approvers, as AMX does not support Fast Formula, but uses their own rule logic.','2011-04-13 22:38:22','2011-04-13 22:38:22',NULL,'Must Have','2.0',NULL),(1235,127,'Approval Routing: Deleted Timecards  (AMX)','For timecards that have been submitted which have triggered the approval routings, the approval flow needs to be interrupted and the approvers need to be notified that the timecard has been deleted.','2011-04-13 22:38:22','2011-04-13 22:38:22',NULL,'Must Have','2.0',NULL),(1236,127,'Approval Routing:  Changes to a Timecard (AMX)','If an approved timecard requires changes, the status of the timecard needs to be reset to a submitted status.  The timecard needs to be routed again for approvals.  The approval routing may be different for a resubmission, as opposed to the original submission, based on the approval rule setup. \n\nIf the approval period is greater than a single timecard period, than all the timecards which make up the approval period will be re-routed for approval based on time entry changes.\n\nIf a timecard has been submitted and has entered an approval routing, the routing process needs to be cancelled, so the updated timecard can re-enter the approval routing.\n\nProcessed Result Changes Only - If the timecard has not had changes to the raw entered time, but for some reason the time calculation rules need to recalculate, which causes changes to the processed results, the timecard should be retriggered for approval.  The reason for this is to give the approver a “heads up” that the processed time has changed, in case it would impact his approval decision.','2011-04-13 22:38:22','2011-04-13 22:38:22',NULL,'Must Have','2.0',NULL),(1237,127,'Approval Routing:  Change of Approvers within Timecard Period (AMX)','The determination of which timecard entries should be sent to which approvers should be determined by the approval rule associated to the approval transaction type.  The approval rule can be defined to either send impacted time entries to the correct approver for each time period section, or to send all time to the valid approver for beginning of timecard or valid approver at end of timecard period.','2011-04-13 22:38:22','2011-04-13 22:38:22',NULL,'Must Have','2.0',NULL),(1238,127,'Business Events of Timecard (Timecard Actions)','The current trigger points for approval include the following actions: manual action or bulk upload of timecards being submitted triggering approval.\n\nü     Submission of timecard\n\nü     Re-submission of timecard\n\nü     Deletion of timecard\n\n \n\nThere should be the ability for users to assign different approval routings for different events.\n\n \n\nDetermination of the approval period is required to determine if approval is needed:\n\nü     A timecard approval period must be complete.  There may be different approval periods for each application to which the timecard is routed. (i.e. Payroll, Projects, etc) These approval periods are not necessarily analogous to the timecard time periods.\n\nü     Data Entered:  certain data is entered in the timecard which would trigger approvals.  This data would be analyzed as part of time categories.  Prior to Fusion, this data would be recognized as fields in mappings related to retrieving applications like Payroll or Projects.','2011-04-13 22:38:22','2011-04-13 22:38:22',NULL,'Must Have','2.0',NULL),(1239,127,'Use of HCM Transaction Model (Time and Labor)','If the timecard approval transaction is incorporated into the HCM Transaction Model, outputs of the transaction model which can be included in the timecard approval transaction include:\n\nA.  Review Page which would include:\n\n·     A single column table showing new data for Create operations\n\n·     A two or three column table showing data changed for Update operations\n\nB.  Transaction Storage which would include:\n\n·     Storing business data as XML (the default operation)\n\n·     Sets up Conflict Management data\n\n·     Allows customer to over-ride the default functions of the Transaction Store (e.g. setting up Status Column handling)\n\n·     Provides callbacks at appropriate points to allow consumer to amend the business data\n\n·     Allows consumer to store their own values in flexfield structures (for custom conflict checking)\n\n·     Allows the business data to be reactivated, for example to edit during approval.\n\n·     Raises an event to call Approvals Integration\n\nC.  Use of Approvals Integration which would include:\n\n·     Notifications to approvers requesting approval.\n\n·     Allowing the Approvals routing to be configured\n\n·     Provides asynchronous call-back to the Transaction Store to process approval result','2011-04-13 22:38:22','2011-04-13 22:38:22',NULL,'Nice to Have','2.0',NULL),(1240,127,'No Locks on Timecards in Approval (Time and Labor)','There are instances when an approver may be opening a timecard notification requiring approval, and at the same time  a timecard user is updating the same timecard.  The approval notification would have a display of the timecard version related to that approval.  Ideally, we could provide an informational message to the approver if someone else submitted a new version simultaneously. \n\nWhen the new version of the timecard is resubmitted, the current approval notification should be cancelled and a new approval notification should be generated for the approvers.  Additionally, it would be a good user experience for the approver if he is accessing the timecard during the approval process and the timecard is in the midst of being updated, to show a message to the approver that the timecard is being edited currently.  However, this may not change the approver’s actions, as the current approval transaction is currently open and active.\n\nWe would not want to lock the timecard from updates during the approval process, as there is no sense of how long the timecard approval process would last for the last version of the timecard.  Locking the timecard when a user has the security access to update the timecard is very frustrating and confusing to the timecard user.\n\nOpen issue:  We will have to see how AMX is dealing with this conflict when a timecard user is accessing an approval transaction (email or worklist notification) and the approval transaction is being cancelled because a new approval transaction is being generated.','2011-04-13 22:38:22','2011-04-13 22:38:22',NULL,'Must Have','2.0',NULL),(1241,127,'Timecard Requiring Your Approval Notification (Manager)','Following  are the key features of the “timecard requiring your approval” notification which will be routed to a timecard approver and can be accessed from the general worklist table or custom worklist table in the Timecards Workarea:\n\n \n\no     Details Section - Human task fields are placed in the first column.\n\n§     Assignee: Recipient\n\n§     From: Requestor\n\n§     Assigned Date: Date and (optional) Time in hours and minutes (no seconds)\n\n§     Expiration Date: Date and (optional) Time in hours and minutes (no seconds)\n\n§     Due Date: appears only when not null.\n\n§     Outcome: appears only when not null.\n\n§     Task Number: Primary object identifier. Needed for trouble-shooting between user and admin.\n\no     Approval Actions – Approve, Reject, Request More Information, Reassign (Transfer or Delegate)\n\no     Timecard Details- summary display of the timecard, including raw and processed time\n\no     Link to View Timecard Details – hyperlink to take user to the timecard view page, which is configured in the Time Entry Page Composer\n\no     Link to Edit Timecard – hyperlink to the timecard to allow the approver to edit the timecard, if they have edit access\n\no     Comments – ability for approver to add comments regarding approval or rejection of the timecard\n\no     Audit Log – display only region to show different users who have taken action on the timecard\n\no     Tabular Action History- Displays the action history from beginning to end in tabular form. This includes past as well as future actions. It allows for editing the list of participants, full and abreviated history, and task snapshot.\n\no     Graphical Action History- a This component displays the action list and process flow as applicable in the system in an easy-to-scan graphical format. This graph is generated by the SOA-BPEL/HT team.\n\n \n\n \n\nOnce the approver takes an action on the notification, it will be cleared from his worklist queue.','2011-04-13 22:38:22','2011-04-13 22:38:22',NULL,'Must Have','2.0',NULL),(1242,127,'Timecard Has Been Approved Notification (Worker)','This is an informational notification which can be routed to the worker, or original submitter of the timecard that the timecard was approved.  The notifications provides the list of approvers who approved the timecard and has 2 action buttons to “Acknowledge” or “Cancel” the notification.  If the user selects the acknowledge button, the notification will be cleared from their worklist.\n\n \n\nThe key sections of this notification are:\n\n·     Details Section - Human task fields are placed in the first column.\n\no     Assignee: Recipient\n\no     From: Requestor\n\no     Assigned Date: Date and (optional) Time in hours and minutes (no seconds)\n\no     Expiration Date: Date and (optional) Time in hours and minutes (no seconds)\n\no     Due Date: appears only when not null.\n\no     Outcome: appears only when not null.\n\no     Task Number: Primary object identifier. Needed for trouble-shooting between user and admin.\n\n·     Timecard Details- summary display of the timecard, including raw and processed time\n\n·     Link to Edit Timecard – hyperlink to the timecard if needed\n\n·     Approver List –table listing the approvers and their action\n\n·     Comments –comments regarding approval or rejection of the timecard\n\n·     Audit Log – display only region to show different users who have taken action on the timecard\n\n·     Tabular Action History- Displays the action history from beginning to end in tabular form. This includes past as well as future actions. It allows for editing the list of participants, full and abreviated history, and task snapshot.\n\n·     Graphical Action History- This component displays the action list and process flow as applicable in the system in an easy-to-scan graphical format. This graph is generated by the SOA-BPEL/HT team. ','2011-04-13 22:38:22','2011-04-13 22:38:22',NULL,'Must Have','2.0',NULL),(1243,127,'Timecard Has Been Rejected Notification (Worker)','This is an informational notification which can be routed to the worker, or original submitter of the timecard that the timecard was rejected.  The notifications provides the list of approvers who rejected  or approved the timecard and has 2 action buttons to “Acknowledge” or “Cancel” the notification.  If the user selects the acknowledge button, the notification will be cleared from their worklist.  Cancelling the notification will not remove the notification from the worklist, but just close the notification.  The comments section should indicate why the timecard was rejected. \n\n \n\nThe key sections of this notification are:\n\n·     Details Section - Human task fields are placed in the first column.\n\no     Assignee: Recipient\n\no     From: Requestor\n\no     Assigned Date: Date and (optional) Time in hours and minutes (no seconds)\n\no     Expiration Date: Date and (optional) Time in hours and minutes (no seconds)\n\no     Due Date: appears only when not null.\n\no     Outcome: appears only when not null.\n\no     Task Number: Primary object identifier. Needed for trouble-shooting between user and admin.\n\n·     Timecard Details- summary display of the timecard, including raw and processed time\n\n·     Link to Edit Timecard – hyperlink to the timecard to allow the worker to edit the timecard, to resolve the reasons for rejection based on the notification\n\n·     Approver List –table listing the approvers and their action\n\n·     Comments –comments regarding approval or rejection of the timecard\n\n·     Audit Log – display only region to show different users who have taken action on the timecard\n\n·     Tabular Action History- Displays the action history from beginning to end in tabular form. This includes past as well as future actions. It allows for editing the list of participants, full and abreviated history, and task snapshot.\n\n·     Graphical Action History- This component displays the action list and process flow as applicable in the system in an easy-to-scan graphical format. This graph is generated by the SOA-BPEL/HT team.','2011-04-13 22:38:22','2011-04-13 22:38:22',NULL,'Must Have','2.0',NULL),(1244,127,'Timecard Requires More Information Notification (Timecard Submitter or Approver)','The worker or initiator of the timecard will receive this notification and  need to respond to the approver with updated comments and submit the notification back to the approver for update.  The key action buttons on this notification are Submit and Cancel.  Once the notification is submitted, it will be cleared from the user’s worklist queue.\n\n \n\nThe key sections of this notification are:\n\n·     Details Section - Human task fields are placed in the first column.\n\no     Assignee: Recipient\n\no     From: Requestor\n\no     Assigned Date: Date and (optional) Time in hours and minutes (no seconds)\n\no     Expiration Date: Date and (optional) Time in hours and minutes (no seconds)\n\no     Due Date: appears only when not null.\n\no     Outcome: appears only when not null.\n\no     Task Number: Primary object identifier. Needed for trouble-shooting between user and admin.\n\n·     Timecard Details- summary display of the timecard, including raw and processed time\n\n·     Approver List –table listing the approvers and their action\n\n·     Comments –comments section in which the user can add more comments to respond to the questions\n\n·     Audit Log – display only region to show different users who have taken action on the timecard\n\n·     Tabular Action History- Displays the action history from beginning to end in tabular form. This includes past as well as future actions. It allows for editing the list of participants, full and abreviated history, and task snapshot.\n\n·     Graphical Action History- This component displays the action list and process flow as applicable in the system in an easy-to-scan graphical format. This graph is generated by the SOA-BPEL/HT team\n\nSee Open Issues on Notification requirements','2011-04-13 22:38:22','2011-04-13 22:38:22',NULL,'Must Have','2.0',NULL),(1245,127,'Timecard Has Been Reassigned for Approval Notification (Worker)','This informational notification is sent to the worker or originator of the timecard to alert them that one of the approvers in the approver list has been changed and approval is reassigned to a new “named” approver.\n\n \n\nThe page actions for this notification is “acknowledge” and “cancel”.  If the user clicks on “Acknowledge”, the notification is cleared from their worklist queue.\n\n \n\nThe key sections of this notification are:\n\n·     Details Section - Human task fields are placed in the first column.\n\no     Assignee: Recipient\n\no     From: Requestor\n\no     Assigned Date: Date and (optional) Time in hours and minutes (no seconds)\n\no     Expiration Date: Date and (optional) Time in hours and minutes (no seconds)\n\no     Due Date: appears only when not null.\n\no     Outcome: appears only when not null.\n\no     Task Number: Primary object identifier. Needed for trouble-shooting between user and admin.\n\n·     Timecard Details- summary display of the timecard, including raw and processed time\n\n·     Approver List –table listing the approvers and their action\n\n·     Comments –comments section in which the user can add more comments to respond to the questions\n\n·     Audit Log – display only region to show different users who have taken action on the timecard\n\n·     Tabular Action History- Displays the action history from beginning to end in tabular form. This includes past as well as future actions. It allows for editing the list of participants, full and abreviated history, and task snapshot.\n\n·     Graphical Action History- This component displays the action list and process flow as applicable in the system in an easy-to-scan graphical format. This graph is generated by the SOA-BPEL/HT team','2011-04-13 22:38:22','2011-04-13 22:38:22',NULL,'Must Have','2.0',NULL),(1246,127,'Approval Periods (Time and Labor)','To continue the flexibility customers currently have, it is important to be able to distinguish timecard periods from approval periods. For example, a timecard period may have aduration of biweekly, but an approval period defined for payroll might be weekly.  The ability for different time consumers to define different approval periods for the timecards to be retrieved allows for the time to be transferred on a timely basis to the time consumer.  Approval periods will be setup in the time consumer set UI, associated to each time consumer who will be retrieving the worker’s timecard data.\n\nApproval periods can span across timecards.  For example, an approval period for Payroll might be weekly, which could start on one timecard and complete on the next timecard.  In this example, when the 2nd timecard has reached the approval period upon submit, the time from the prior timecard needs to be consolidated with the time from the 2nd timecard and routed for approval.  In this example, it is important to note that the submission of the first timecard would not trigger approval, it was upon the submitting of the 2nd timecard that it needed to be determined if the overlapping approval period was met.\n\nSome examples of when timecard periods and approval periods are not aligned:\n\nIn some cases customers want to have a short Timecard Period and a long Approval Period. This is because the customer wants to force users to submit time on a frequent basis yet not burden their approvers with frequent approvals.  \nFor example: Daily Timecard Period and Weekly Approval Period   \n\nIn some cases customers (eg Santos) want to have a short approval period and a longer timecard period. This is because the customer wants to move the time that’s been entered through to the time consumer as quickly as possible. For example, a weekly timecard period and a daily approval period. Users submit there timecard whenever they enter time and this time is then sent to the approver and can be transferred to the time consumer without waiting till the end of the week.\n\nIn the case where there is more than one time consumer for a given worker\'s time, it may be that 2 or more of the Time Consumers have their own, \'natural\' approval period. For example Projects might have a Weekly Expenditure Period and Payroll a Bi-monthly payroll period. In this case, at least one of the approval periods must differ from the Timecard Period.','2011-04-13 22:38:22','2011-04-13 22:38:22',NULL,'Must Have','2.0',NULL),(1247,127,'Approval Rules (AMX)','In order to correctly route the timecard data to approvers, there are evaluations of the timecard that need to be done which would continue the same functionality as Approval Styles and Approval Rules in EBS Time and Labor R12.  Firstly, it needs to be determined if approval is needed on timecard submission, based on the approval period defined for the timecard.  Then if approval is required, it needs to be determined, what type of approval needs to be done, such as auto-approval or routing to one or more approvers.    The approval rules defined in AMX will determine what timecard data is collected for approval and to whom it is routed for approval, and how the routings will occur.\n\nThe approvers may or not be in the same application (i.e. Payroll, Projects).  Once the type of approval is determined, it needs to be determined what timecard data needs to be packaged and transferred to the approvers, based on rule criteria, which can include the summing of data using time categories.  Time categories allow for the summing up of time against different time entry fields present on the timecard.  These time categories can sum up data that is specific to an application, like Payroll or Projects, or it can simply sum up a specific group of time entries, such as overtime or bonuses which require approval.\n\nThe approval rules made available in AMX need to provide the following flexibility:\n\no     Need the ability to define approval rules by role , to allow time to be approved by role (project manager(derived by Project ID) , payroll manager, timekeeper, manager).\n\n \n\no     Need the ability to define approval rules based on data values in the timecard ( assignment status (based on Core HR status) , summarization, timecard status, project manager, overtime, hours exceeding “X” hours, Project ID exists, Hours Type of “Overtime, Special Compensation”. Time Categories will allow ways of summarizing values, to look for “All Values” or “Only specific values” to allow for “fragmented approval”.\n\n \n\no     Need the ability to define approval rules to support “fragmented approval”  - to filter only certain rows of timecard data to the correct approver.\n\n \n\no     Need the ability to define approval rules to bypass normal approval flow and allow auto-approval – (based on conditions like, time entered by manager, timekeeper, project manager, payroll manager)\n\n \n\nNote:  Please refer to the Appendix on Seeded Approval Rules, based on approval rules that were delivered in EBS OTL R12.','2011-04-13 22:38:22','2011-04-13 22:38:22',NULL,'Must Have','2.0',NULL),(1248,127,'Approval Rules:  Conditions  (AMX)','When creating approval rules for timecard approvals, every organization has different needs for when time needs approval.  Approval conditions can be based on who the employee is, how an employee is associated to some entity, what type of time is reported or if certain limits are met.  It is important that a user can combine any attributes which are associated to a worker in HCM as well as time attributes, which can be defined and combined with time categories.  Time categories can also be used in “exceed limits” rules.  The following fields are examples of core HR, Payroll, Projects and Time and Labor fields which should be available as attributes for timecard approval rules:\n\nCore HR\n\n·     Job\n\n·     Position\n\n·     Legislative Data Group\n\n·     Legal Entity\n\n·     Organization\n\n·     Assignment Status\n\n·     Shift\n\n·     Work Schedule\n\n·     Person Type\n\n·     Company\n\n·     Cost Center\n\n·     Department\n\n·     Grade\n\n·     Location\n\n·     Collective Agreement\n\n·     Person\n\n·     HCM Group\n\n \n\n \n\nPayroll\n\nPayroll Element\n\nPayroll Period\n\nBalance\n\nPayroll Cost Allocation\n\n \n\nProjects\n\nProject\n\nTask\n\nProject Status\n\nLabor Rate\n\nExpenditure Type\n\n \n\nTime and Labor\n\nTime Category\n\nSetup Option Profile','2011-04-13 22:38:22','2011-04-13 22:38:22',NULL,'Must Have','2.0',NULL),(1249,127,'Approval Transaction Type: Approval Rule Association to Workers','In order to provide flexibility among different populations of workers, it is critical that a user can group their approval rules into a logical set and associate them to different groups of workers.  Some workers may only require auto approval of time, whereas other groups of workers may require different types of time to be approved.  Being able to associate different levels of timecard approval requirements to different workers provides more efficiency for overall approval processing.\n\nTo accomplish this goal, different Approval Transaction Types will be defined in AMX, with groupings of Approval Rules.  These Approval Transaction Types will be associated to the time consumer in the Time Consumer Set UI.  The worker will be associated to the Approval Transaction Type based on the Time Consumer Set assigned to his Time and Labor Worker Processing Setup Profile.  The options for the Approval Transaction Type choicelist will either be “Auto-Approval”, which will bypass the AMX flow, or one of the seeded Approval Transaction Types in AMX.','2011-04-13 22:38:22','2011-04-13 22:38:22',NULL,'Must Have','2.0',NULL),(1250,127,'Auto Approval of Loaded Time and Labor)','Time can be loaded into Time and Labor from an API from any time collection system.  There should be a mechanism in which the user can configure imported time to be “stamped” with an approved status.  In this manner, the time should not be routed through any approval process, it should just be approved and ready to be transferred to another application. \n\nHowever, any time which is loaded into Time and Labor will be processed through application validations (validations of the time consumers which will retrieve the time).   If any time that is validated is in error, then it cannot be stamped as approved.  The timecard errors will need to be resolved before they can be “stamped” as approved.  The Approval Transaction Type option of “Auto-Approve” defined in Section 2.3.29 can be utilized for this scenario, when the errors are cleared and the timecards are resubmitted.','2011-04-13 22:38:22','2011-04-13 22:38:22',NULL,'Must Have','2.0',NULL),(1251,127,'Forced Approval  (AMX)','For timecards which are not slated for auto approval, but need to be routed to approvers, there are times that the timecards may need to be forced through approvals.  There may be a timing issue in which the timecards need to get processed to payroll immediately, or there may be a breakdown in the approval routing in which approvers are not available.  There needs to be a process in which a user can easily determine the timecards which are pending approval and be able to approve them.  The ability to do this approval may require special “override approval” security.\n\nExample of the terminated worker scenario:\n\nIn the event that a worker is terminated (voluntarily or involuntarily), there needs to be a way to move the timecard through the approval process to get the accurate recorded time to payroll for payment.  At issue is that the approval period may not be met even if the timecard is submitted, so would not automatically route to the AMX routing rules.\n\nA worker submits a timecard which only contains 2 days of a weekly Payroll approval period. The worker is terminated and therefore will not be submitting the next timecard which would \'fill up\' the Time Approval Transaction. There are two days which need to be paid but the timecard submission would not complete the approval period to trigger AMX approvals.\n\nThere is an enhancement request for AMX to provide and API for Forced Approval, which is not available as of yet - Enhancement 7495226.  To utilize this API we would need to specify parameters of when to call this API and for which worker’s timecards.  As this API is not currently available, the main design solution for Fusion v2 is the following:\n\nIn Fusion v2, in order to expedite timecards being pushed to a time consumer, we will not force the approval but we will leave the approval process as it is, but we will force the timecards for immediate transfer. Using the Group Time Entry user interface, the administrator can select workers and their related timecards which need to be immediately transferred.  We are calling this process “Forced Transfer”.  Going forward with this solution, that will permit the timecard to carry on its normal approval route and hence allows the approver to reject the timecards if wrong/missing entries were made. If the timecard gets rejected, after getting transfered in a time consumer application, after the timecard gets corrected and approved, in the next transfer to the time consumer adjustement will be made.\n\nAn alternate solution for terminated workers is that we can subscribe to event triggers such as terminations of employees, which would trigger the adjustment of approval periods to end on the employee’s termination date, to expedite the approval of the required timecards.','2011-04-13 22:38:22','2011-04-13 22:38:22',NULL,'Must Have','2.0',NULL),(1252,127,'Approval of Blank Timecards (AMX)','For businesses which always require timecards to be generated and approved for all time periods for their employees, it is important that even a blank timecard can be approved.  A blank timecard means that no time entries have been made for the employee for the time period.  It is critical that a blank timecard can still be routed through the approval process, whether it is for “auto approval” or for specific approval routing.','2011-04-13 22:38:22','2011-04-13 22:38:22',NULL,'Must Have','2.0',NULL),(1253,127,'Approval Statuses (Time and Labor)','As stated in the Report Time FDD, there are derived statuses which will be displayed in the Timecard Status field for the timecard related to approvals:\n\nApproved: When all time entries have been approved within that timecard\n\nRejected:  When at least one time entry has been rejected in the timecard\n\nSubmitted:  When the timecard has been submitted without errors to be approved\n\nOpen Design Issue:  There is the use case in which the timecard has been submitted but is not routed for approval because the approval period is greater than the timecard period.  In this instance, the timecard will be waiting for the next timecard to be submitted to see if the approval period has been met for it also to be routed for approval.  As a result, this timecard is in a “holding pattern” until the approval period is met.  A possible additional status for this condition can be “Pending Approval”, to indicate that the timecard has been completed but is not yet ready for the approval flow.','2011-04-13 22:38:22','2011-04-13 22:38:22',NULL,'Must Have','2.0',NULL),(1254,128,'No Name',' ','2011-04-13 22:38:22','2011-04-13 22:38:22',NULL,'Must Have','2.0',NULL),(1255,129,'No Name','  ','2011-04-13 22:38:22','2011-04-13 22:38:22',NULL,'Must Have','2.0',NULL),(125