ecards in progress.  (Design Issue:  Timecards in Progress may need to be configured at the User \\tPreference level to determine which timecard statuses should be displayed in this region).</dd>\\n        <ol><dt>\\n\\\n  \\tThe filters for this table will be Timecard Status and month.  The actions from this table will be to create timecard.  The \\tcolumns in the table are :</dt>\\n        <dd>o\\tTimecard Period : hyperlinked to take user to that timecard in edit mode, if it is not hyperlinked they do not have access rights to edit that timecard</dd>\\n        <dd>o\\tTimecard Status : In Error, Rejected, Submitted, Draft, Approved, Transferred</dd>\\n        <dd>o\\tReported Hours : total number of reported hours in the timecard</dd>\\n        <dd>o\\tOvertime Hours : total number of overtime hours for the timecard determined by seeded time category</dd>\\n        <dd>o\\tSubmission Date : the date the timecard was submitted (if in submitted status)</dd>\\n        <dd>o\\tApproval Chain : icon which triggers a pop up of the approval graph display from AMX of the flow of approvers, if has \\tentered Approval flow.  If the timecard has not yet been submitted, the Approval Chain icon will not display.</dd>\\n        <dd>o\\tAudit Data : will display a read only checkmark to indicate that this timecard contains a time audit entry page for change and late requirements</dd>\\n        <dd>o\\tView Summary : will display an icon, when clicked will take the user to a read only form of the timecard which is configured in the Time Entry Page Composer as a viewable timecard layout.</dd>\\n        <dd>o\\tDelete ? delete icon to allow the user to delete the timecard.  If the user does not have access rights to delete the timecard, the icon will be grayed out</dd>\\n        </ol></ol></ol>        \\n      \\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:00'),(2889,'Feature',963,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: \"Worker Timecards Work Area : Local Area: Current Time period\"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:03:52 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:03:52 Z\npriority: \nid: 963\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 105\ndescription: \"\\n        \\xC2\\xA7\\tLists Timecard Period in display only mode\\n        \\xC2\\xA7\\tLists Timecard Due On \\\"Date/Time\\\"  (if implement Timecard Submission Due Date) in display only mode\\n        \\xC2\\xA7\\tDaily Punch Summary (if worker has clock time in layout)\\n        \\xC2\\xA7\\tWill list current date and total hours logged thus far\\n        \\xC2\\xA7\\tEnter Daily Punch : button which will trigger a pop up screen for clocking in or out and entering timecard \\t\\t\\tfields with it.  (Design to be determined in Web Clock FDD)\\n      \\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:00'),(2890,'Feature',964,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: \"Worker Timecards Work Area : Local Area: Timecard Preferences section\"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:03:52 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:03:52 Z\npriority: \nid: 964\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 105\ndescription: \"\\n        \\xC2\\xA7\\tLists Default Number of Blank Rows (editable by worker via pencil icon) : worker can change the default number of blank rows displayed on a new timecard\\n        \\xC2\\xA7\\tDefault Template : display of worker\'s default private template, with ability to change the template with a pop up\\n\\n      \\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:00'),(2891,'Feature',965,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: \"Worker Timecards Work Area : Local Area: Accrual Balances Table\"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:03:52 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:03:52 Z\npriority: \nid: 965\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 105\ndescription: \"\\n       Table listing of the leave balance accruals with an as of date.  The content \\n       of this table will be determined in Timecard Integration with Absence Management \\n       FDD.\\n      \\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:00'),(2892,'Feature',966,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: \"Worker Timecards Work Area : Local Area: Project Plan Snapshot\"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:03:52 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:03:52 Z\npriority: \nid: 966\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 105\ndescription: \"\\n       Snapshot of the worker\'s current scheduled tasks in the Projects project plan      \\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:00'),(2893,'Feature',967,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: \"Worker Timecards Work Area : Local Area:Common Calendar Display\"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:03:52 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:03:52 Z\npriority: \nid: 967\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 105\ndescription: \"\\n       Display of the worker\'s current common calendar display of holidays, absences, availability and hours worked (Common \\tCalendar design to be determined )\\n       \\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:00'),(2894,'Feature',968,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: \"Worker Timecards Work Area : Local Area:Time Balance Monitor\"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:03:52 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:03:52 Z\npriority: \nid: 968\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 105\ndescription: \"\\n       Listing of the Balances made available along with measuring against defined thresholds\\n       \\n      \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:00'),(2895,'FunctionalWorkUnit',105,'destroy','1','--- \nname: Time and Labor Analytics\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:03:52 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:03:52 Z\nbusiness_area_id: 195\nid: 105\nparent_id: \niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:00'),(2896,'Feature',969,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Time Calculation Rules\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:03:52 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:03:52 Z\npriority: \nid: 969\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 106\ndescription: If the Rules Processing Engine is the heart of the TCR module, the Time Calculation Rules are the soul.  Without Time Calculation rules, the engine will have nothing to process and the TCR module is just an empty box.  The Time Calculation rules will contain the actual business logic that the customer wants to apply to the time.  Time Calculation Rules will be written as Fast Formulas, a business processing language already widely used throughout HCM for other types of business rules (e.g. Benefits, Payroll, etc.).\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:00'),(2897,'Feature',970,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: OTL Rules are consistent across the OTL Application\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:03:52 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:03:52 Z\npriority: \nid: 970\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 106\ndescription: OTL will deliver rules of different types (TER, TCR, TAR, and TIR) that are defined and assigned in a similar manner.  The Rule engine may or may not be the same (based on Development design) but should appear the same functionally.\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:00'),(2898,'Feature',971,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: \"Enable Configurable Sort options for Timecard Entries prior to application of (TER, TCR, TAR, TIR (future)) Rules \"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:03:52 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:03:52 Z\npriority: \nid: 971\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 106\ndescription: |-\n  The Rule set for each type of rule (TER, TCR, TAR, etc) must allow for a sort option, where OTL Development delivers the standard sort option used in EBS R12.  The Sort Option will reference a choice list where customer defined functions may be registered, and displayed for selection.  The sort options will then affect the execution of rules, since specific entries processed first may result in different end values.\n  \n  OTL Development will also deliver information on how to define new sort options and how to register them.\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:00'),(2899,'Feature',972,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Allow for overrides of Calculated Rule Results\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:03:52 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:03:52 Z\npriority: \nid: 972\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 106\ndescription: \"OTL Development will allow for Layouts defined with an editable rule result section to be assigned to timekeepers to manually adjust calculated results.  The Timecard containing adjusted results should be \\xE2\\x80\\x98identifiable\\xE2\\x80\\x99 so that a message may be shown explain how the results were arrived at.\"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:00'),(2900,'Feature',973,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Viewing the Calculation Results\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:03:52 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:03:52 Z\npriority: \nid: 973\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 106\ndescription: This is closely related to the previous feature in that customers want to be able to control not only when to perform the calculations, but also to determine when and how to show it to the users (if at all).  This is related because obviously you can only show the calculations results after you performed the calculation itself.  But customers can opt not to show the results at all (even though the calculation was done) or perform the calculation on submission, but only show the result after review or approval.\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:00'),(2901,'Feature',974,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Customer control over when to apply Time Calculation Rules\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:03:52 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:03:52 Z\npriority: \nid: 974\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 106\ndescription: We need to provide a feature that allows our customers to determine when the rules get applied to the entered timecard.  In other words, where (if at all) in the Timecard Entry flow the time calculation rules will get applied.  In addition, this feature needs to allow customers to postpone the calculation when they feel this is needed.  A typical example is an incomplete timecard, there might not be a point in performing any calculations on such a timecard (although I would assume that this would mean they save the timecard and they would select not to perform calculations on a Saved Timecard).\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:00'),(2902,'Feature',975,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Control over which Time Business Rule to apply and when\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:03:52 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:03:52 Z\npriority: \nid: 975\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 106\ndescription: \"One of our more critical requirements is the ability to be able to determine the \\xE2\\x80\\x9Cflavor\\xE2\\x80\\x9D of rule that gets applied depending on what the user enters on his timecard.  Probably the most frequent occurrence is that overtime isn\\xE2\\x80\\x99t being calculated the same in every state in the US.  How it gets calculated literally depends on where (in which state) the time was actually worked.  In other words, which flavor of Overtime Rule gets fired depends on what the user enters as location on his timecard (location being an attribute of the time).  We need to allow customers to use every attribute or combination of attribute (we\\xE2\\x80\\x99ll use Time Categories) as a \\xE2\\x80\\x9Cdecider\\xE2\\x80\\x9D.  Obviously, at setup, administrators do not know what the user is going to enter so they need to cater for all and we need to provide them with a feature that allows them to do this.  As a result a \\xE2\\x80\\x9Crule\\xE2\\x80\\x9D is going to be a combination of different Fast Formula that contain different business logic.  Which of these Fast Formulas will fire for that rule will then depend on the attributes on the timecards.\"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:00'),(2903,'Feature',976,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Total Control over Results of Rules\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:03:52 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:03:52 Z\npriority: \nid: 976\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 106\ndescription: \"Customers not only want control over the measure or IN OUT columns, they want to have total control over the attributes resulting from the TCR Rules as well.  In the TCR Rules Results, we will allow them to \\xE2\\x80\\x9Cset\\xE2\\x80\\x9D attribution based on a RETURN value from the Rule\\xE2\\x80\\x99s Fast Formula or specify the attribute value in the Rules Results themselves.  Either way, this will provide them with the flexibility to control any attribute on the resulting calculated time entries.\\n\\n\\\n  Also, because we are allowing calculations on all kinds of time, meaning for all kinds of attributes, it becomes very hard for us in development to know exactly what needs to be the result of a rule, in fact it is impossible to know and most likely it is different for different customers, so opening this up for our customers is necessary and unavoidable.\"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:00'),(2904,'Feature',977,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Time Balances\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:03:52 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:03:52 Z\npriority: \nid: 977\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 106\ndescription: Some time business rules require time to be aggregated over a period of time.  Just like we do not know what kind of business rules customers want to apply to their time, we generally do not know how they want to aggregate time.  Not only do we not know the period but we also do not know what kind of time they want to group.  Depending on the attribution time might be in our out of the balance.  Therefore, we need to let our users setup their own Time Balances and we will leverage Payroll Balances to accomplish this.  This introduces a dependency on Core Payroll to ensure that Payroll Balances work with Time (instead of pay values).  Because we are able to use Payroll Balances, this feature requires no coding.  However, we need to seed the basic components of a balance (Balance Types and Balance Dimensions) so our users can create balances in the first place.\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:00'),(2905,'Feature',978,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Rule Assignment\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:03:52 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:03:52 Z\npriority: \nid: 978\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 106\ndescription: \"Once the rules have been created, they need to somehow be \\xE2\\x80\\x9Cassigned\\xE2\\x80\\x9D to people so that those rules get applied to those employees\\xE2\\x80\\x99 timecards.  Therefore we will create a new preference or preference segment that allows customers to create a preference and pick a Time Calculation Rule Set, and then assign this preference per the preference module to individuals or groups using the available preference criteria.\"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:01'),(2906,'Feature',979,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Work Day Definition\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:03:52 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:03:52 Z\npriority: \nid: 979\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 106\ndescription: \"Normally, a day is considered to start at 00:00:00 and end at 23:59:59 but for rules this definition is not always useable.  Sometimes it is necessary for a rule to interpret a day slightly different and a day would go from say 22:00 to 21:59:59 the next day, overlapping 2 real days.  As rules are sometimes dependant on a day, it is important that we let our customers decide when these \\xE2\\x80\\x9Cwork days\\xE2\\x80\\x9D start and end so their rules apply as they see fit.  A typical example is a premium that depends on a day, say Sunday.  If the shift starts on a that day \\xE2\\x80\\x93 Sunday 22:00 \\xE2\\x80\\x93 but runs into the next day \\xE2\\x80\\x93 Monday 06:00 \\xE2\\x80\\x93 then they employee might be entitled to the Sunday Premium the whole shift, even though he only really worked 2 hours on Sunday, and the rest on Monday.  Or he might not be.  This is entirely up to the customer and as a result we need to let them decide when a day starts or stops in relation to a Rule.\"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:01'),(2907,'Feature',980,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Ability to use HR Holiday Calendar in TCR\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:03:52 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:03:52 Z\npriority: \nid: 980\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 106\ndescription: \"This feature will allow TCR to become \\xE2\\x80\\x9Choliday aware\\xE2\\x80\\x9D.  This awareness can then be used in rules or to determine which rules need to be used depending on the Holiday.  This feature will rely heavily on the HR Calendar module that stores the corporate Holiday Calendar.  In TCR, you will then be able to link Rules to this calendar and as a result get different rules on those Holiday Days.\"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:01'),(2908,'Feature',981,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Time Calculation Templates\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:03:52 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:03:52 Z\npriority: \nid: 981\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 106\ndescription: \"TCR Templates are probably the feature that will make or break TCR.  Because the TCR module allows for so much flexibility, creating even the simplest of rules could become a pretty daunting task.  We need to try to avoid this at all costs and this is where templates will come in.  Therefore, for certain rules (and we still need to determine which ones) we will provide \\xE2\\x80\\x9Crule templates\\xE2\\x80\\x9D.  These rule templates will consists of a Fast Formula Template, and a form which can be used to answer a few questions that are needed to transform the template into a real Fast Formula.  Behind the scenes it will also create the Rule Results (again based on answers from the user), the processing rule (when the Fast Formula needs to fire), potentially a new balance and anything else that is necessary for it to become a rule that can be used in a Time Calculation Rule Set.\\n\\n\\\n  On the other side of the spectrum, we know that we cannot create formulas for all possible scenarios and so we also need to expose forms that our customers can use to create rules from scratch.  This would mean a form to create Fast Formulas (re-using the Payroll / HR Fast Formula Form), Rule Template (defining inputs and outputs then shown on the Rule Page)TCR Rules, TCR Rule Results and Balances.  T&L will make the Template page a mandatory step in defining new rules, placed over the formula, and making the actual rule creation a bit more functional.\"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:01'),(2909,'Feature',982,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: Tags\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:03:52 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:03:52 Z\npriority: \nid: 982\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 106\ndescription: \"Littered throughout the requirement document, there are references to a so called \\xE2\\x80\\x9CRule Type\\xE2\\x80\\x9D.  The purpose of this type was that we might be able to classify rules into these types and make it easier for our users to find a particular rule using the Rule Type.  This Rule Type however is probably too restrictive.  We will not be able to stripe our data by Business Group anymore, nor by Legislation (this is a functional decision; rules are to be global), so this type should also replace that functionality.  Finally, some rules cannot be easily classified and users can create their own rules for which we would have no type handy.  All this means that we need more flexible way to classify rules so that customers can find the rules they need.\\n\\n\\\n  We opted for a tagging (aka labeling) mechanism.  This allows our customers to add as many tags as the want to their rules that will make it easy for them to find them back later on.  E.g. a threshold rule could have the following tags: us overtime 8.  These 3 tags would indicate that the actual threshold rule is a rule that applies to the US, calculates Overtime, and has a threshold of 8.  Whenever the users need to search for a Rule, they can supply any combination of tags and a list of rules matching those tags will appear.  For example, they might want to see all rules that have \\xE2\\x80\\x9Cus\\xE2\\x80\\x9D as a tag (presumably these are rules applicable to the US legislation, but the point is that it could really mean anything the customer wants it to be).\\n\\n\\\n  The tagging infrastructure will also be made available for other entities in HXC, and we might use it as well for TCR fast Formulas.\"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:01'),(2910,'FunctionalWorkUnit',106,'destroy','1','--- \nname: Time and Labor Time Calculation Rules and Rule Sets\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:03:52 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:03:52 Z\nbusiness_area_id: 195\nid: 106\nparent_id: \niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:01'),(2911,'Feature',983,'destroy','1','--- \nscope: \nname: No Name\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:03:52 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:03:52 Z\npriority: \nid: 983\nfunctional_work_unit_id: 107\ndescription: \"  \"\niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:01'),(2912,'FunctionalWorkUnit',107,'destroy','1','--- \nname: \"Time and Labor Public Timecard Template \"\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:03:52 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:03:52 Z\nbusiness_area_id: 195\nid: 107\nparent_id: \niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:01'),(2913,'BusinessArea',195,'destroy','1','--- \nname: FDDs\ncreated_at: 2011-04-13 22:02:35 Z\nupdated_at: 2011-04-13 22:02:35 Z\nid: 195\nparent_id: \niteration_id: \n','2011-04-13 22:37:01'),(2914,'BusinessArea',196,'create',NULL,NULL,'2011-04-13 22:37:04'),(2915,'FunctionalWorkUnit',108,'create',NULL,NULL,'2011-04-13 22:37:04'),(2916,'Feature',984,'create',NULL,NULL,'2011-04-13 22:37:04'),(2917,'FunctionalWorkUnit',109,'create',NULL,NULL,'2011-04-13 22:37:04'),(2918,'Feature',985,'create',NULL,NULL,'2011-04-13 22:37:04'),(2919,'Feature',986,'create',NULL,NULL,'2011-04-13 22:37:04'),(2920,'FunctionalWorkUnit',110,'create',NULL,NULL,'2011-04-13 22:37:04'),(2921,'Feature',987,'create',NULL,NULL,'2011-04-13 22:37:04'),(2922,'Feature',988,'create',NULL,NULL,'2011-04-13 22:37:04'),(2923,'Feature',989,'create',NULL,NULL,'2011-04-13 22:37:04'),(2924,'Feature',990,'create',NULL,NULL,'2011-04-13 22:37:04'),(2925,'Feature',991,'create',NULL,NULL,'2011-04-13 22:37:04'),(2926,'Feature',992,'create',NULL,NULL,'2011-04-13 22:37:04'),(2927,'Feature',993,'create',NULL,NULL,'2011-04-13 22:37:04'),(2928,'Feature',994,'create',NULL,NULL,'2011-04-13 22:37:04'),(2929,'Feature',995,'create',NULL,NULL,